NARRATOR ROLE:
- Narrator scenes show environmental shots, symbolic imagery, or emotional atmosphere (NO characters)
- CRITICAL: The script subject must NEVER be a person. Subject = place, object, time, or abstract concept.
- Narrator script LENGTH: 10–20 characters (Korean) / 20–40 characters (English)
- Scripts UNDER 10 characters cause TTS audio defects — always write 10+ chars.
- Narrator scripts should be SHORTER than A/B dialogue lines, but still 10+ chars.

✅ ALLOWED Narrator Script Patterns (subject = environment/mood/abstract, 10+ chars):
- "오래된 카페에 햇살이 든다." (13자, subject: 카페/햇살)
- "창밖으로 차가운 빗소리." (11자, subject: 빗소리)
- "길고 어색한 침묵이 흐른다." (13자, subject: 침묵)
- "10년이라는 긴 시간." (10자, subject: 시간)
- "창밖, 노을이 지고 있다." (12자, subject: 노을)

❌ BAD Narrator Scripts (too short, TTS fails):
- "어색한 침묵." (6자) → TOO SHORT, expand to "길고 어색한 침묵이 흐른다."
- "빗소리." (3자) → TOO SHORT, expand to "창밖으로 차가운 빗소리."

❌ FORBIDDEN Narrator Script Patterns (subject = person/character action):
- "두 사람이 마주 앉았다." (subject: 두 사람 → FORBIDDEN)
- "그녀가 고개를 돌렸다." (subject: 그녀 → FORBIDDEN)
- "그는 천천히 걸어갔다." (subject: 그 → FORBIDDEN)
- "서로를 바라보았다." (implied subject: people → FORBIDDEN)

Narrator Position Roles (all examples 10+ chars):
- Opening (scene 1): Set the scene atmosphere/location. e.g., "오래된 카페, 오후의 햇살."
- Transition (mid): Convey mood shift or time passage. e.g., "길고 무거운 침묵이 흐른다."
- Closing (final): Wrap with emotion or reflection. e.g., "창밖, 노을이 지고 있다."

